Variables Reclassification, Organization and Preparation

converting ‘registration_init_time’ and ‘expiration_date’ into date format

kkbox_train$registration_init_time = ymd(kkbox_train$registration_init_time)
kkbox_train$expiration_date = ymd(kkbox_train$expiration_date)

changing some variables into factors and checking their levels

kkbox_train[,c("msno","city","gender","registered_via")] = lapply(kkbox_train[,c("msno","city","gender","registered_via")],factor)

gender has 3 levels

levels(kkbox_train$gender)
## [1] ""       "female" "male"

We decided to keep the ‘blanks’ factors of gender since we suspect they may impact the churn rate.
We will label them as “Unknown”

levels(kkbox_train$gender)[levels(kkbox_train$gender)==""] = "unknown"

verfying the absense of missing values

sum(is.na(kkbox_train))
## [1] 0

we will create a new variable that indicates the average discount a user received

kkbox_train$avg_discount = (kkbox_train$total_list_price - kkbox_train$total_amount_paid) / kkbox_train$num_of_transactions

replace or remove unnessary column ‘total_amount_paid’ and ‘total_list_price’ add new column ‘avg_list_price’ b/c we will be working with only averages

kkbox_train$avg_list_price <- kkbox_train$total_list_price/kkbox_train$num_of_transactions
kkbox_train <- kkbox_train %>% select(-total_amount_paid, -total_list_price)

clarifying the ‘average_amount_paid’ variable by changing its name

colnames(kkbox_train)[which(colnames(kkbox_train) == "average_amount_paid")] = "avg_amt_paid_per_tran"

split the ‘kkbox_train’ into ‘train’ and ‘test’ dataset

set.seed(1)
split <- sample.split(kkbox_train$msno,SplitRatio = 0.7)
train <- kkbox_train[split,]
test <- kkbox_train[!split,]
rm(split)

Data Visualization and Further Preparation for Numeric Variables

train_plot1 <- Filter(is.numeric,train) %>%  
  gather (key, value,-is_churn) #gathering all numerics for a more generalized visualization

looking how numeric variables affect the predicted value

ggplot(train_plot1,aes(x=factor(is_churn),y=value,fill=key))+
  geom_bar(position='dodge',stat='summary',fun.y='mean')+
  facet_wrap(~ key, scales="free")+
  theme(text = element_text(size=10))

from the boxplot, ‘bd’ contains a lot of negative ages and > 100 ages

length(which(train$bd <=0 | train$bd >= 100)) / nrow(train) #54.8% of all observations are unreasonable
## [1] 0.5480558

checking the potential influence of “reasonable” ages on our predicted value

no_outliers <- train[!which(train$bd <=0 | train$bd >= 100),]
ggplot(no_outliers,aes(x=factor(is_churn),y=bd, fill = factor(is_churn)))+
  geom_bar(position='dodge',stat='summary',fun.y='mean')

ggplot(no_outliers,aes(x=factor(is_churn),y=bd, fill = factor(is_churn)))+
  geom_boxplot()

since the the unreasonable ages are the majority of all observations and b/c it doesn’t seem like the distribution of age is significantly difference for users who churned and didn’t, we will remove the variable ‘bd’ from our dataset

train = train %>% select(-bd)
rm(no_outliers)

from the multiple boxplots image, ‘total_secs’ has a lot of negative values

boxplot(train$total_secs) 

boxplot(abs(train$total_secs)) #the negatives don't look like typos due to their large absolut value

sum(train$total_secs<0)/nrow(train) #observations with negative 'total_secs' account for 1.9% of the entire 'train' dataset
## [1] 0.01884955
#thus, we decided to remove them 
train <- train[!which(train$total_secs<0),]
boxplot(train$total_secs) #potential positive outliers

Data Visualization for non-numeric variables

number of users by gender: We checked how a user’s gender affects churn rate. It appeared that there was no difference in the churning rate between males and females, yet, the unidentified genders had lower churning rate relative to the identified ones.

ggplot(train, aes(x = factor(is_churn), fill = factor(is_churn)))+
  geom_bar(position='dodge') + 
  facet_wrap(~ gender)  +labs(x="is_churn",y="number of users")

sum of number of transactions by city: We used a bar plot to look at the total number of transactions performed by users from each city and then factored each city by the predictive variable. Thus, we discovered that most of our users (51.6%) came from city ‘1’. Also, cities 4, 5, 13, 15, and 22 produced significant number of users as well.

ggplot(train, aes(x = city, y = num_of_transactions, fill = factor(is_churn)))+
  geom_bar(position='dodge',stat='summary',fun.y='sum')

number of users in each city by gender:We looked at the number of users that came for each city in our data and segmented it by the user’s gender. It allowed us to identify that city ‘1’ was a major source for users who didn’t specify their gender relatively to all other cities in our data.

ggplot(train, aes(x = city, fill = factor(gender)))+
         geom_bar(position='stack')+
          facet_wrap(~ is_churn)

mean of the number of transactions by registeration channel: Lastly, we investigated the average number of transactions by the registration channel a user used to see how it influences our predictive variable. We discovered that registration methods 3, 4, and 9 had significant difference in the average number of transactions between users who churned and didn’t churn.

ggplot(train, aes(x = registered_via, y = num_of_transactions, fill = factor(is_churn)))+
  geom_bar(position='dodge',stat='summary',fun.y='mean')
